# SRA data pipeline conventions

## Sample identity and FASTA files

- Treat the **`Run` column** (NCBI SRA accession: `SRR*`, `ERR*`, `DRR*`) as the **sample ID**: one CSV row with a valid `Run` is one sequencing sample.
- **FASTA filenames** use that accession as the base name: `{Run}.fasta.gz` (for example `SRR5894020.fasta.gz`).
- **Layout** matches `scripts/download_sra_data.py`: for a data CSV whose filename stem is `<study_name>`, files live under `fasta/<study_name>/` at the repo root (e.g. `fasta/AAM+13/SRR5894020.fasta.gz`). Scripts that read sequences should resolve paths the same way.

## `fasta/` directory and runtime

- In this project, **`fasta` may be a symlink** to a large external directory (e.g. a shared sequence store). A **full pass over every run** can take a **long time** because processing must **read every base** in each **gzip FASTA** (I/O and decompression bound). Do not assume “small repo” timings for batch scripts over all runs.

## Long-running scripts

- Any script that **iterates over many runs or large FASTAs** should expose **visible progress** (e.g. current study, run index / total, optional ETA or per-study summary). Prefer **flushed stdout** or a single updating status line (`\r`) so logs stay usable; print a **newline** before unrelated output so progress lines do not corrupt the terminal.
